00:02:00.090 --> 00:02:05.520
- [David] Before we get to the question
and answer session, I'd like to say just a

00:02:05.700 --> 00:02:14.090
few words about the range of things that
have come up in this symposium. As Roger

00:02:14.270 --> 00:02:23.150
said at the beginning, we decided to make
our focus not how did language begin but

00:02:23.330 --> 00:02:29.650
how did language come to have the form it
has and we've included some other things

00:02:29.830 --> 00:02:40.810
that we think go along with that. One
thing that we've seen today is the

00:02:40.990 --> 00:02:47.980
outstanding array of different types of
language that have either been studied in

00:02:48.160 --> 00:02:57.710
some depth or mentioned in passing and
that have come up in this symposium. We

00:02:57.890 --> 00:03:07.840
particularly wanted to include both spoken
and sign languages and take advantage of

00:03:08.020 --> 00:03:17.070
the fact that sign languages, being so
much younger than spoken languages, afford

00:03:17.250 --> 00:03:25.450
us a chance to see language at earlier
stages of its development, than we can get

00:03:25.630 --> 00:03:35.960
very readily in spoken languages. We saw
that new linguistic forms emerge in spoken

00:03:36.140 --> 00:03:48.910
language as well in Carmel O'Shannessy's
talk where we sew how children in this

00:03:49.090 --> 00:03:56.170
Australian community have put together
bits and pieces of languages used around

00:03:56.350 --> 00:04:03.410
them and created something entirely new.
There were references to pidgins and

00:04:03.590 --> 00:04:14.070
creoles and other such newly arising types
of language as well as two brand new

00:04:14.250 --> 00:04:21.770
languages like the Central Taurus Sign
Language and the Al Sayyid Bedouin sign

00:04:21.950 --> 00:04:31.190
language in southern Israel. All of these
things there's such a wide range of

00:04:31.370 --> 00:04:39.020
different types of language sprouting up
around us in different parts of the world

00:04:39.200 --> 00:04:45.700
and offer us a chance to see languages at
the very earliest stages, yet we must keep

00:04:45.880 --> 00:04:53.760
in mind that this is not the same thing as
what the earliest stages of human language

00:04:53.940 --> 00:05:02.130
must have been like. For all of these are
languages spoken or signed by individuals

00:05:02.310 --> 00:05:11.510
with modern human brains and that's
probably a very big difference, and the

00:05:11.690 --> 00:05:24.310
last talks on language in the brain
provided three different perspectives on

00:05:24.490 --> 00:05:33.110
what the brain is doing in use of language
or when the individual is doing linguistic

00:05:33.290 --> 00:05:43.270
tasks as well as particularly in professor
Mayberry's talk. How exposure to language,

00:05:43.450 --> 00:05:53.620
to any language, in the early years, the
earliest years of life is essential to

00:05:53.800 --> 00:06:03.280
being able to fully master and acquire a
human language.

